name: ABAP
description: A business programming language created by SAP.

name: Actionscript
description: Primarily used for writing programs for Adobe's Web and mobile multimedia Flash platform.

name: Ada
description: Originally designed for the U.S. Department of Defense, Ada is used for applications where reliability is critical, such as aerospace control systems.

name: Apex Code
description: A business application language designed for utilizing Salesforce.com's cloud resources.

name: ASP.NET
description: A scripting language developed by Microsoft for dynamic websites hosted on its IIS Web server.

name: Assembly
description: Writing assembly code requires considerable expertise, but it allows the creation of high-speed software that can run directly on a computer processor.

name: C
description: C is used to write software where speed and flexibility is important, such as in embedded systems or high-performance computing.

name: C#
description: Created by Microsoft for developing software for the .NET framework, which supports many applications running on Windows.

name: C++
description: Essentially a version of C with built-in support for "objects"--self-contained modules of code and data--C++ proved to be a natural fit for software driven by graphical user interfaces.

name: Clojure
description: An attempt to revive Lisp by making it compatible with the same "virtual machine" that supports Java programs.

name: Cobol
description: Created in the late 1950s for business and financial applications, COBOL software still drives critical systems in many large institutions.

name: CoffeeScript
description: An alternative to JavaScript that's intended to be simpler to use.

name: D
description: Intended as a successor to C++, D is still a relatively new language.

name: Delphi
description: A derivative of Pascal used for Windows applications, owned by the Embarcadero Delphi company. Open-source implementations under the rubric of Open Pascal exist for other platforms.

name: Eiffel
description: An object-oriented language designed closely with an integrated development environment for rapid development.

name: Erlang
description: Created by Ericsson for embedded telephony applications, the release of Erlang as an open-source language in 1998 boosted its popularity among programmers developing applications that have to handle many concurrent tasks.

name: Forth
description: Originally designed to control radio telescopes, Forth is still used for applications such as boot loaders and other firmware.

name: Fortran
description: Created in the 1950s, Fortran is designed for high-performance scientific and engineering computing.

name: Go
description: Created by Google, Go has built-in support for programs that need to exchange information while running concurrently on different computers.

name: Haskell
description: Designed for applications where reliability is important.

name: HTML
description: A specialized language for describing the appearance and content of Web pages.

name: J
description: Primarily used for analytics and mathematical programming.

name: Java
description: Designed to allow the creation of programs that can run on different platforms with little or no modification, Java is a popular choice for Web applications.

name: JavaScript
description: A scripting language used primarily to add functionality to Web browsers on the fly, allowing the creation of complex Web pages.

name: Ladder Logic
description: Intended for the development of industrial programmable logic controllers.

name: Lisp
description: Created in the 1950s, Lisp became widely used by artificial intelligence researchers, but it has seen a decline in more recent years.

name: Lua
description: A scripting language often used to make other applications programmable, especially in the animation and gaming domains.

name: Matlab
description: A scripting language for MathWorks' Matlab computing environment, Matlab is designed for numerical computing tasks, such as engineering or scientific simulations.

name: NetLogo
description: Designed for teaching programming and for the construction of scientific models.

name: Objective-C
description: Adding support for objects--self-contained modules of code and data--to the C language, Objective-C was Apple's favored language for writing applications for OS X or iOS, but this may change with the introduction of Swift.

name: Ocaml
description: An object-oriented language with an emphasis on supported software reliability.

name: Perl
description: A scripting language often used as the "glue" in complex systems.

name: PHP
description: A scripting language primarily designed to support dynamic websites.

name: Processing
description: Originating at MIT, Processing has been developed to make it easy for artists, designers, and hobbyists to generate visualizations.

name: Prolog
description: Originating in the artificial intelligence community, Prolog is primarily used as a teaching and research tool.

name: Python
description: A scripting language that is often used by software developers to add programmability to their applications, such as engineering-analysis tools or animation software.

name: R
description: Designed for programming statistical analysis and data-mining applications.

name: Ruby
description: A scripting language designed to offer greater support for objects than other such languages.

name: SAS
description: A data- and statistical-analysis language.

name: Scala
description: Programs written in Scala, an alternative to Java, can run on the same "virtual machine" as Java programs.

name: Scheme
description: Originally a teaching language, this variant of Lisp is still used for applications such as the App Inventor for Android, which allows the rapid development of mobile applications.

name: Scilab
description: An open-source alternative to the Matlab numerical computing language.

name: Shell
description: A catchall term for a number of frameworks that allow scripting of operating system command-line instructions.

name: SQL
description: A specialized language designed to query and manipulate databases.

name: TCL
description: A scripting language intended for rapid prototyping and supporting the Tk graphical user interface used primarily with Unix systems.

name: Verilog
description: A hardware description language used in the creation and analysis of electronic circuits.

name: VHDL
description: A hardware description language used in the creation and analysis of electronic circuits.

name: Visual Basic
description: Microsoft created Visual Basic to allow rapid development of Windows applications but no longer supports it. A descendant, Visual Basic.NET, which is still supported, works with the more modern .NET framework.

name: Arduino
description: Based on Processing, the native language for the Arduino microcontroller has become the basis of a huge number of home-brew and prototype devices.

name: Swift
description: Apple's latest language for creating iOS and OS X software. The language is compatible with existing Objective-C code and was open sourced this year to increase adoption among coders.

name: ColdFusion
description: NA

name: Cuda
description: Created by graphics-chip maker Nvidia, Cuda allows programmers to tap the power of GPUs for general-purpose computing.

name: IDL
description: NA

name: Julia
description: Julia is designed for statistical and scientific computing while retaining compatibility with legacy libraries written in Fortran or C.

name: LabView
description: Created by National Instruments, LabView is designed for data acquisition and industrial control.

name: Opa
description: NA

name: Rust
description: With its first stable version released this year, Rust is designed to make concurrent systems easier to program reliably.
